comment.body:
@caryoscelus: Well, looks like it's the sad truth. Realizing all the drawbacks of the Android since the fifth version, or what's more important nowdays, the modern hardware design (without removable batteries, card readers, Mini Jacks, etc), such devices are less reliable than Pocket PCs or even Symbian-powered phones used to be. So they are just too unreliable to be called with an acronym which includes the word "assistant".
Looks like many people don't even remember an acronym like this because they don't need a real smartphone. They still use it as a feature phone, and main features still consist of making calls (regardless of using the GSM network or IM apps), but also running a modern Web browser^W^W JS runtime and all the fancy consumer apps. Android is a real "consumer OS". It even consumes more hardware resources than a normal desktop OS, so a good i3-powered laptop that handles complex games such as Life is Strange or Minecraft (with hi-res textures) and modern Web (barely, through K-Meleon), can't run Android-x86 smoothly, especially in a VM.
The real major reason we can't stick to such reliable devices and OSes (speaking even about desktop OSes, like Windows XP) is that we're already stuck to modern Web browsers.
All in all, after 3 years of using Debian as my primary desktop OS, and as the proprietary software (such as Pocket PC) is not fancy nowdays (formally), I wish I had a desktop Linux distribution on my mobile devices. And I find three solutions to it:
1) keep using my HTC HD2 or buy a used Nokia N900;
2) use a combination of a netbook and a cellphone which is just capable of tethering;
2.1) replace the cellphone with an LTE dongle and set up SIP for "legacy" phoning services;
3) design and assemble my own RasPi-based PDA. Well, as I got an A on "Drawing and CAD" for the term, looks like this is the way.
Chroot-based apps like Linux Deploy were used to be a good and high-compatible solution, but they won't resolve the hardware design issues.
P.S. And reflashing a RasPi-based PDA would be much easier, as RasPi does store the firmware on a removable storage.
